1 baseline for those metrics prior to implementing mental health promotion activities under the program.
2 (3) (a) Contingent on and within appropriations for the program, the office of public instruction shall
3 award grants to school districts displaying the greatest need, preparation, and promise of successfully
4 implementing mental health promotion activities under the program. If possible, the office of public instruction
5 shall award grants to districts in a manner that ensures diversity of district size and geography.
6 (b) The office of public instruction shall award annual grants to school districts of not less than
7 $10,000 or more than the lesser of an amount equal to $25 for each enrolled student in a participating school in
8 the prior school year or $50,000.
9 (c) A school district awarded a grant must receive the grant for 2 years and may reapply for a
10 second 2-year grant cycle.
11 (d) A school district receiving a grant under the program shall deposit the grant funds in the
12 district's miscellaneous programs fund and use the grant funds only for the costs of implementing mental health
13 promotion activities.
14 (4) (a) A school district receiving a grant under the program shall report to the office of public
15 instruction by July 15 of even numbered years. The report must include the following:
16 (i) an accounting of expenditures of grant funds;
17 (ii) a summary of mental health promotion activities implemented under the grant; and
18 (iii) an evaluation of the effectiveness of the grant in improving the mental health of students in
19 participating schools, including, if possible, the specific metrics under subsection (2)(e).
20 (b) The office of public instruction shall report, in accordance with 5-11-210, to the education
21 interim committee a compilation of the reports received under subsection (4)(a) and an agency evaluation of the
22 implementation of the program.
23 (5) As used in this section, the term "mental health promotion activities" means locally determined,
24 developmentally appropriate activities that may occur in or out of school aimed at improving the mental health
25 of the entire population of students at a school, decreasing stress, anxiety, and mental illness, and reducing the
26 incidence of violence, bullying, substance use, and self-harm. The term may include but is not limited to:
27 (a) modifications to the school schedule, such as later start times or block scheduling;
28 (b) reconfiguring of the school to increase the feeling of community and students being known by
